column7: Most of my Q&A time was taken by comments and self promotion of other people's work
column8: but I am sure other participants have documented this accurately on this app. I just wanted to say that after my talk I was approached by FirstName LastName who condescendingly proceeded to tell me what I should have said in my talk ("that's what people would have liked to hear" -- his suggestion was off topic). Then FirstName LastName also came to basically tell me that "we did this 20 years ago".  This made me realise that this kind of thing (old male profs cornering me after my talk to tell me what/how I should have done my talk/work) actually happens regularly. So I figured it would be worth mentioning in this survey (btw thanks for doing this!!). Interestingly enough
column9: when FirstName LastName (male grad student) gave his talk about pretty much the same work that I presented
column10: that we have been doing together
column11: FirstName LastName had a question for him in the Q&A
column12: so I thought " I'd better go look out for FirstName after his talk" but LastName did not show up like he did after my talk. I obviously can't draw any conclusions from this but somehow I just couldn't help noticing. Thanks
